B.Ee=new A.aR("What is the most common modifiable risk factor for stroke?","Hypertension - present in ~70% of stroke patients. It is the single most important modifiable risk factor for both ischemic and hemorrhagic stroke.")
B.DH=new A.aR("What percentage of strokes are ischemic vs hemorrhagic?","Ischemic: ~87%. Hemorrhagic: ~13% (10% intracerebral hemorrhage, 3% subarachnoid hemorrhage).")
B.DQ=new A.aR("What are the 5 subtypes of ischemic stroke per the TOAST classification?","1. Large artery atherosclerosis\n2. Cardioembolism\n3. Small vessel occlusion (lacunar)\n4. Stroke of other determined etiology\n5. Stroke of undetermined etiology (cryptogenic)")
B.E5=new A.aR("What does the circle of Willis consist of?","Anterior communicating artery, bilateral anterior cerebral arteries (A1 segments), bilateral internal carotid arteries (terminal portions), bilateral posterior communicating arteries, and bilateral posterior cerebral arteries (P1 segments). It provides collateral blood flow between the anterior and posterior circulations.")
B.DD=new A.aR("What are the lenticulostriate arteries and what do they supply?","Small penetrating branches of the M1 segment of the MCA. They supply the putamen, globus pallidus, caudate head, and internal capsule. They are the most common site of hypertensive lacunar infarcts.")
B.Eq=new A.aR("What does the anterior cerebral artery (ACA) supply?","The medial surface of the frontal and parietal lobes, including the motor/sensory cortex for the lower extremity, supplementary motor area, and the medial frontal cortex (motivation, micturition center).")
B.DT=new A.aR("What does the middle cerebral artery (MCA) supply?","The lateral convexity of the hemisphere: motor/sensory cortex for face and upper extremity, Broca area (dominant, posterior inferior frontal gyrus), Wernicke area (dominant, posterior superior temporal gyrus), insular cortex, and optic radiations (temporal component).")
B.E7=new A.aR("What does the posterior cerebral artery (PCA) supply?","The occipital lobe (primary visual cortex), inferomedial temporal lobe, thalamus (via thalamoperforating and thalamogeniculate branches), and the splenium of the corpus callosum.")
B.DO=new A.aR("What is a transient ischemic attack (TIA)?","A transient episode of neurological dysfunction caused by focal brain, spinal cord, or retinal ischemia WITHOUT acute infarction on imaging. Most last <1 hour. The 90-day stroke risk after TIA can be estimated with the ABCD2 score.")
B.Es=new A.aR("What is the ABCD2 score and what does it predict?","Predicts stroke risk after TIA.\nA = Age >=60 (1 pt)\nB = BP >=140/90 (1 pt)\nC = Clinical features: unilateral weakness (2 pts), speech disturbance without weakness (1 pt)\nD = Duration: >=60 min (2 pts), 10-59 min (1 pt)\nD = Diabetes (1 pt)\nTotal 0-7; higher scores = higher 2-day stroke risk.")
B.DV=new A.aR("What is the NIH Stroke Scale (NIHSS)?","A 15-item standardized clinical scale (0-42) quantifying neurological deficit severity in acute stroke. Assesses: consciousness, gaze, visual fields, facial palsy, motor arm, motor leg, limb ataxia, sensory, language, dysarthria, extinction/inattention. Higher score = more severe stroke.")
B.Eb=new A.aR("What is the modified Rankin Scale (mRS)?","A global disability/outcome scale ranging from 0 to 6.\n0 = No symptoms\n1 = No significant disability\n2 = Slight disability (independent)\n3 = Moderate disability (needs some help)\n4 = Moderately severe disability\n5 = Severe disability (bedridden)\n6 = Dead\nScores 0-2 = functionally independent.")
B.DW=new A.aR("What is the Functional Independence Measure (FIM)?","18-item assessment of functional independence, scored 1 (total assist) to 7 (independent) per item. Total score 18-126. Domains: self-care (6 items), sphincter control (2), transfers (3), locomotion (2), communication (2), social cognition (3). Motor FIM and cognitive FIM subscores available.")
B.DB=new A.aR("What is the first-line imaging study in acute stroke and why?","Non-contrast CT head. It is fast (seconds), widely available, and highly sensitive for acute hemorrhage (appears hyperdense/white). It is essential to exclude hemorrhage before considering thrombolytic therapy. Early ischemic changes may not be visible for 6-12 hours.")
B.E3=new A.aR("What is DWI on MRI and why is it important in stroke?","Diffusion-weighted imaging detects restricted water diffusion from cytotoxic edema within minutes of ischemic onset. It is the most sensitive MRI sequence for acute ischemic stroke. Restricted diffusion appears bright on DWI and dark on the ADC map.")
B.En=new A.aR("What is a lacunar infarct?","A small (<15 mm) subcortical infarct caused by occlusion of a single penetrating arteriole due to lipohyalinosis or microatheroma. Common locations: putamen, thalamus, caudate, pons, internal capsule. Associated with hypertension and diabetes. Produces classic lacunar syndromes.")
B.DE=new A.aR("What are the major non-modifiable risk factors for stroke?","Age (risk doubles each decade after 55), sex (higher in men, but women have higher lifetime risk), race/ethnicity (African Americans have 2x risk), family history/genetics, and prior stroke or TIA.")
B.E1=new A.aR("What are the major modifiable risk factors for stroke?","Hypertension (most important), atrial fibrillation, diabetes mellitus, hyperlipidemia, smoking, physical inactivity, obesity, excessive alcohol use, carotid stenosis, and sickle cell disease.")
B.Ef=new A.aR("What is the Barthel Index?","A 10-item ordinal scale (0-100) measuring basic ADL performance: feeding, bathing, grooming, dressing, bowel control, bladder control, toilet use, transfers (bed to chair), mobility (level surface), and stairs. Score of 100 = independent in basic ADLs.")
B.Eh=new A.aR("What is the ischemic penumbra and why is it clinically important?","The ischemic penumbra is the area of brain tissue surrounding the infarct core that is hypoperfused but still viable (electrically silent but structurally intact). It is the target of acute reperfusion therapies (tPA, thrombectomy). Without reperfusion, the penumbra progresses to infarction over time.")
