k=A.ag("Board Pearl: Xanthochromia","Xanthochromia (yellow discoloration of CSF supernatant) is the most reliable LP finding for SAH. It indicates prior bleeding and takes 6-12 hours to develop. If a patient presents >6 hours after headache onset with a negative CT, xanthochromia on LP confirms SAH. The classic way to distinguish SAH from a traumatic tap is that SAH shows consistent RBCs across all tubes and xanthochromia, while a traumatic tap shows decreasing RBCs and no xanthochromia.")
